==========================================
Why Do We Need Helm?
==========================================

Imagine you joined a company as a DevOps Engineer.

The company has 4 projects.

Project 1 - HRMS
Project 2 - E-Commerce
Project 3 - Banking Portal
Project 4 - CRM

Each project has around 30 features (microservices).

Examples:

HRMS
------
Employee Service
Payroll Service
Attendance Service
Leave Service
Notification Service
...

E-Commerce
------------
Product Service
Order Service
Payment Service
Cart Service
Inventory Service
...

Each feature needs Kubernetes resources like:

• Deployment
• Service
• ConfigMap
• Secret
• Ingress
• HPA

That means one feature requires around 6 YAML files.

Now calculate:

4 Projects

×

30 Features

=

120 Features (Microservices)

Each feature needs 6 YAML files.

120 × 6

=

720 YAML files

Now imagine the company has three environments.

Development
QA
Production

720 × 3

=

2160 YAML files

Now think...

• If the image version changes?
• If the replica count changes?
• If a new environment is added?
• If a ConfigMap changes?
• If we need to roll back?

Will you edit thousands of YAML files manually?

No.

That is exactly why Helm was introduced.

==========================================
Solution
==========================================

Instead of maintaining thousands of YAML files,

we create one reusable Helm Chart for each service.

Then we use different values files for each environment.

values-dev.yaml

values-qa.yaml

values-prod.yaml

The templates remain the same.

Only the configuration changes.

Deployment becomes as simple as:

helm install employee ./employee-chart -f values-dev.yaml

helm install employee ./employee-chart -f values-qa.yaml

helm install employee ./employee-chart -f values-prod.yaml

This saves time, reduces errors, and standardizes deployments across all environments.